Node.Notes: Probably vocative, but could also be O of "you judge."
(SYNTAX) NPNP used since plural cannot be in apposition to singular. So, seen as conjoined pair without conjunction.
Uncertain. Many change text to "may they be crushed/withered like weeds on a path." Text might yield something like "when he draws the bow, let his arrows [wither/be blunted] like they will wither.

Assuming that first two clauses portrayed the people as dissolved and flowing away and idea continues with their withering (but wishing that their effectiveness [with shooting arrows; perhaps for harm?] wither like their persons).
Uncertain. Tree assumes "[Let him be" as a snail that melts away while it moves along, [like] a woman's stillborn child who has not seen the sun."
Uncertain. Some prefer beeswax/worm/abortion. Most go with snail.
(SYNTAX) Perfect plural form is problematic for all attempts at translation. Everyone has changed this to singular (or stillborn child to plural children) or changed it to imperfect jussive.

Highly uncertain with many different proposals. Tree assumes "Before your pots can feel the thornbush, whether green or ablaze, he will sweep him away," general sense that before the wicked judges can enjoy the fruit of their wickedness, God will sweep them away like a tempest.
Bramble bush that does not produce fruit/product, but was used for fire as brushwood.
(SYNTAX) Use of a plural attribution to Elohim "God" is unusual (though Elohim does sometimes occur with plural verbs, e.g., 2s7:23).
